NAME
    sort - sort lines of text files

SYNOPSIS
    sort [OPTION]... [FILE]...

DESCRIPTION
    Write sorted concatenation of all FILE(s) to standard output.
    When no FILE is given, or FILE is '-', read standard input.

    Lines are sorted in the locale's collating sequence by default.
    Use -n for numeric sort or -k to sort on specific fields.

OPTIONS
    -b, --ignore-leading-blanks
        Ignore leading blanks when finding sort keys.

    -d, --dictionary-order
        Consider only blanks and alphanumeric characters.

    -f, --ignore-case
        Fold lowercase characters to uppercase for comparison.

    -g, --general-numeric-sort
        Compare according to general numeric value (handles floats).

    -i, --ignore-nonprinting
        Consider only printable characters.

    -n, --numeric-sort
        Compare according to string numerical value.

    -h, --human-numeric-sort
        Compare human-readable numbers (e.g., 2K, 1G).

    -r, --reverse
        Reverse the comparison result.

    -s, --stable
        Stabilize sort; do not sort equal lines relative to each other.

    -t SEP, --field-separator=SEP
        Use SEP as the field delimiter instead of non-blank-to-blank
        transition.

    -k POS1[,POS2], --key=POS1[,POS2]
        Sort via a key starting at POS1. If POS2 is given, the key ends
        at POS2. Each position is FIELD[.CHAR][FLAGS].

    -u, --unique
        Output only the first of equal lines.

    -m, --merge
        Merge already-sorted files; do not sort.

    -c, --check, --check=diagnose-first
        Check that the input is sorted; do not sort.

    -o FILE, --output=FILE
        Write result to FILE instead of standard output.

    -z, --zero-terminated
        Line delimiter is NUL, not newline.

    --version
        Output version information and exit.

    --help
        Display help and exit.

EXAMPLES
    sort file.txt
        Sort file alphabetically.

    sort -n numbers.txt
        Sort numerically.

    sort -rn scores.txt
        Sort numerically in reverse (largest first).

    sort -t: -k3 -n /etc/passwd
        Sort passwd by UID (field 3, colon-delimited, numeric).

    sort -u names.txt
        Sort and remove duplicate lines.

    sort -k2,2 -k1,1 data.txt
        Sort primarily by field 2, secondarily by field 1.

    sort file1.txt file2.txt | uniq
        Merge two files and deduplicate.

EXIT STATUS
    0   Success, or input already sorted (with -c).
    1   Input not in order (with -c).
    2   Error occurred.
